indicators.title: PDO 1 Number of technologies that are being made available to farmers and other end users
indicators.description:
Technology refers to the tools, methods or machinery that are used to support agricultural enterprise. There are many categories of agricultural technologies within the production to marketing value chain, and these include mechanical, biological, chemical, and agronomic innovations.  For APPSA new varieties denote those released in the past 5 years since the commencement of the program, i.e. from 2008 onwards.

Availability will be measured by whether seed or agronomic and postharvest practices are being produced and distributed, or a technology has been or is being promoted by the public or private sector. Technologies will be disaggregated by commodity and according to whether they address a cross cutting priority – such as climate change adaptation, gender, nutrition.
“Farmer”: an individual involved in crop and animal production for food, income or raw materials.
“End User”: Consumers/companies that utilize crop and animal produce.

indicators.title: PDO 2 Proportion of Lead Farmers in targeted areas who are aware of an improved technology promoted by the Project
indicators.description:
Lead farmers represent a group of innovative and successful farmers within the local community who are committed to training their fellow farmers on agriculture methods and technologies.
“Targeted areas” - Areas where the project is being implemented.
“Awareness” - Knowing about a technology through extension services and/or other methods of dissemination e.g. field days, agriculture shows, fairs, training.

indicators.title: PDO 3 Number of technologies generated or promoted by the Project in one country that are released in another country
indicators.description:
“Technology generated” - innovation developed.
“Technology promoted” - innovation made available.
“Technology released in another country” - innovation available in at least two countries.

indicators.title: PDO 4 Number of direct project beneficiaries ('000)
indicators.description:
Direct beneficiaries refers to the persons (e.g. Lead Farmers, contact farmers, other farmers and their dependent family members living in the same household) in the project target region who in the first instance utilize project outputs (i.e., knowledge, and technologies) AND their immediate household members.

Household members are included in the beneficiary count of dissemination projects as the project is intended to bring changes in their livelihood too.

indicators.title: Number of staff trained per research centre in management and leadership (% female)
indicators.description:
Training is defined as a learning activity for participants involving: 1) a setting intended for teaching or transferring knowledge, skills, or attitudes; 2) formally designated instructors or lead persons; and 3) a defined curriculum, learning objectives, and outcomes.


This indicator will track the number of staff trained in leadership and management. Participants should attend at least 90% of total course hours to be considered as completing a course. People attending more than one training should be counted once for each training they complete.

indicators.title: Number of clients (research and advisory service staff) days of training in management and leadership training (% female)
indicators.description: Number of days of training in management and leadership. This indicator uses the following equation to calculate the number of client days of training: (training days) x (number of people completing each training) = Person days of training supported by APPSA. Only people who complete the entire training course are counted for this indicator.
